May 2 2005	Excellent value good location nice apart-hotel	We stayed at the Envoy Club for 7 nights from 14th to 20th April 2005. After reading one of the more recent reviews on the website we were a little worried before we checked in, however we were very pleasantly surprised by the quality of our accommodation. We had booked a studio room, and although we didn't get an upgrade like other guests, the room was more than adequate for our needs. The service we'd had from Envoy Club when booking the room and with follow up queries was very prompt and friendly. I had found a special rate on Expedia for 3 of the 5 nights we booked and emailed them to ask if they could match it as I always prefer to book direct with the hotel. They matched the rate, and when I confirmed my booking, extended it for the whole 5 nights - we paid $179 per night plus taxes (for Brits, that worked out at around £100 per night).The lobby is small, but you have to remember this is not a hotel - it is an apartment block, and Envoy Club own the first 3 or 4 floors of apartments that they rent out to guests on a short term basis. There are no normal hotel facilities, such as a bar or restaurant or large lounge or lobby - if this is important to you don't stay here. There is a fitness room, business centre and laundry, but we didn't use these so can't comment on them. The receptionist was a little scary at first, but we were super friendly to her and her mood brightened. Two days into our stay we decided that NY was so great that we were going to have to stay an extra couple of days. The receptionist accommodated us with no fuss and even let us keep the special rate we were paying for the extra 2 nights. By the end of our stay we were getting tips from her on where to go, and she was teasing us about the amount of shopping we were doing - so all in all friendly service.The room was large by any standard, and as I understand it, particularly for New York. It was all very clean, and our sheets were fine! it was fairly stylishly done, but not over the top modern. There were 2 large windows in the room and it didn't feel too closed in.We had a queen size bed (the receptionist was worried this wouldn't be big enough for my 6'2&quot; other half, but it was fine), a small sofa, a small dining table and 2 chairs. There was cable TV, a VCR and CD player. There were two large cupboards (closets) one was a walk-in which was great and gave us loads of storage space. The kitchen was great, although we didn't use it other than to make coffee and keep milk in the refrigerator. If you were staying for longer though it had all the equipment you'd need to make simple meals - oven, hob, microwave, pots and pans etc - they all look fairly clean.The bathroom was also a good size, it took us a while to work out the temperature control for the shower, but we got there eventually - and very clean, with plenty of towels.We got maid service every day (sometimes a she was little too keen, wanting to come in and clean before we'd left for the day) so the place was always spotless, including the maid cleaning our coffee cups and coffee pot every day.The location is pretty good, although a little out of the main action. It's about 4 crosstown blocks to the subway (about 10 - 15 min walk at an easy pace) and 5 blocks to the Empire State Building. There are a couple of good bars nearby, plenty of pharmacies, convenience stores and delis. We were grateful for the more peaceful location at the end of a busy day, as we had no street or outside noise in our room at all (but we were at the back).My only gripes (and pretty minor ones at that) - there was no way we could find to adjust the air-con. The weather when we were there was positively summer like 70-80 degrees, so it didn't matter too much, but we might have been cold if it were cooler outside. Also the air-con was quite noisy. The other gripe - no full length mirror! How strange in a hotel!I would have no hesitation recommending this place to anyone who isn't that worried about the full on hotel atmosphere, and wants to stay in a quieter neighbourhood.	
