Mar 5 2005 	Going going downhill!	I have stayed several times here in the last year and it keeps getting worse on each visit. My most recent visit in January was my last. Every time I have checked in I have been greeted by a staffer who was busier with their own personal phone calls, friends visiting, food deliveries, eating, reading magazines, etc., to provide a decent greeting, but this last time took the cake! The desk clerk could not be bothered to TURN AROUND and greet me for several MINUTES, speaking to me while seated reading a magazine with their back to me. Is there no management on premise? I have never seen any! Every simple request is typically greeted with NO and bad attitude and if you call downstairs for anything from the room, half the time the phone will ring and ring with no answer! One visit, on a weekday evening while I was trying to get some sleep before a big meeting, a dog next door barked continually, but nothing could be done and the dog yapped for hours into the night because the front desk clerk was gone at 10pm! One of the the desk clerks can also be seen in the evenings slumping in a chair in the lobby complaining loudly about having to work ... Lovely ambience for a hotel. The rooms were once quite nice, but now all the carpeting is stained or has holes and bleached splotches on every floor, both in the hallways which are now a bit dank and soiled and uninviting as well as in the rooms. The toilets either fail to flush or overflow it seems on every other visit. They now even post a warning about it rather than fix the problem! The showers NEVER drain, leaving the tub almost overflowing by the end of your shower. The AC units lately do not work very well, sometimes not at all. Every room I have stayed in has a definite smoky smell, even when it is supposed to be a non-smoking room. The &quot;Frette&quot; linens are not, and they are in TATTERS. Sincerely, the sheets put on the bed are ripped and torn and frayed. The maid and management must know this, but if they allow the front desk clerks to be as rude as they are, they just do not care! The rooms are large, I have stayed in the studios and one bedrooms, but they are generally not cleaned very well and lately look quite grimy. It is just not worth it to stay here anymore regardless of the room size. This hotel has seen better days and is going down the tubes unless it freshens up and hires more professional staff.	
Feb 13 2005	Best kept secret	One of the best kept secrets in New York City is the Envoy Club. I took my husband there in January for a combo dance and comedy weekend in NY. He likes to dance and I like the comedy so we were going to Carolines and out dancing two nights in a row and we needed somewhere to recuperate both days (Thursday &amp; Friday). I did my research for days before and came up with the Envoy Club on E 31 and First Ave. It was perfect!!! It is not just a hotel- it is a home away from home. The apartment - that's right apartment- was fully equipped with kitchen (everything in it), wonderful walk-in closets and a great bathroom. As it happens, it rained the next morning of the first day there and the room came with a huge umbrella. Did I mention that the hotel is on several floors within a business and residential building so you feel right into the neighborhood. They have an exercise room on the floor that I stayed on, too. I don't know if this is the usual, but I have stayed everywhere from Canada to Florida and this was the best place for the price I have ever stayed. I could not believe the reasonable price they charged. I am sure that the next time we plan to have a partying weekend or just a break away, it will be there. 	
Nov 16 2004	Traveller's Worst Nightmare--Homelessness	My husband and I recently visited New York City to support a friend who was running in the marathon. Of course, this is one of the busiest weekends in the city and almost every decent hotel was booked. About one month prior to the trip, we reserved a room at the Envoy Club for the weekend. When we arrived late on a Friday night, we were told that someone moved our reservation to the following Monday through Thrusday instead of Friday through Monday. I guess we were lucky that we even caught the front desk clerk...as she was about to head home for the night and leave the check in desk unattended-don't know what we would've done then. Needless to say, I had received no notification of the reservation change (since it was handwritten in pencil on the &quot;computerized print out&quot;) and had both my hotel web page and email confirmations in hand. Besides, if we had made a change, would we be standing there? The hotel had booked someone in our place...so the hotel was full. We then knew what homelessness felt like. We thought our first night in New York would be spent on a bench in Grand Central Station. After about an hour and a half of calling other hotels, the Envoy Club did finally find us a hotel about 5 blocks away. They only had a smoking room, but at this point, we would take anything. The Envoy Club agreed to pay the rate difference (only verbally--refused to put this in writing). After a call to the new hotel, I was comforted the rates would be taken care of. Finally, at 2:30 am, we checked into a hotel...smokey or not, we had a bed on Park Avenue. Unfortuantely, by check out on Monday morning, the rate difference still had not been resolved with the Envoy Club. After a few heated calls to the Envoy Club Management, the bill was resolved and I thought our Envoy Club nightmare was over. Now, one week later a receive another confirmation from the Enovy Club as a reminder of my upcoming stay. This place just can't get it right. I really hope that we're cancelled!This was a horrible first experience for a stay in New York. I definitely recommend sticking with the &quot;Name Brand&quot; hotels if possible for a visit to such a big place...or at least avoid this hotel with all you've got!	
